{"title_page": "2014 in British radio", "text_new": "{{Year nav topic5|2014|British radio|British television|British music|British film}}\nThis is a list of events in British radio during 2014.\n\n==Events==\n\n===January===\n*1 January \u2013 [[Jazz FM (UK)|Jazz FM]] stops broadcasting on the national [[Digital One]] multiplex, but continues to be available on DAB in London, online and through satellite television.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2013/12/jazz-fm-leaves-national-dab-digital-radio/ |title=Jazz FM leaves national DAB digital radio |publisher=Radio Today |date=5 December 2013 |accessdate=13 December 2013}}</ref> Its Digital One slot is temporarily taken over by the return of [[Birdsong (digital radio channel)|Birdsong Radio]], with plans for a permanent replacement in February.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/new-national-dab-station-to-launch-in-feb/ |title=New national DAB station to launch in Feb |publisher=Radio Today |date=1 January 2014 |accessdate=1 January 2014}}</ref>\n*2 January \u2013 The morning's edition of [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' is guest edited by musician [[PJ Harvey]], with items includes a Thought for the Day from [[WikiLeaks]] founder [[Julian Assange]] and a segment in which [[John Pilger]] criticises US President [[Barack Obama]] for not closing the Guantanamo Bay detention camp. The content prompts [[Labour party (UK)|Labour]] MP [[Tim Austin]] to brand it as the programme's worst ever edition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/today-today-branded-worst-edition-ever/ |title=\"Today\" today branded worst edition ever |publisher=Radio Today |date=2 January 2014 |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\n*3 January \u2013 Former [[BBC Radio 1|Radio 1]] and [[Classic Gold GEM|GEM-AM]] presenter Jenni Costello joins internet station Solid Gold Gem to present ''Ready, Steady 80s'', a weekly programme dedicated to hits from the decade.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2013/12/ex-bbc-radio-1-host-joins-internet-station/ |title=Ex-BBC Radio 1 host joins internet station |publisher=Radio Today |date=23 December 2011 |accessdate=23 December 2013}}</ref>\n*6 January \u2013 It had been reported on 30 December 2013 that [[Hot Radio]] would close at 18:00,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2013/12/hot-radio-bournemouth-to-close-next-week/ |title=Hot Radio Bournemouth to close next week |publisher=Radio Today |date=30 December 2013 |accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref> but the station remains on air after the deadline had passed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/hot-radio-continues-despite-closure-news/ |title=Hot Radio continues despite closure news |publisher=Radio Today |date=6 January 2014 |accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref>\n*8 January \u2013 [[Smooth Radio]] announces that weekend breakfast presenter [[Daryl Denham]] has left the station with immediate effect. His shows will be taken over by [[Emma B]] on Saturdays and Eamonn Kelly on Sundays.<ref name=RT-2014-01-08>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/daryl-denham-exits-globals-smooth-radio/ |title=Daryl Denahm exits Global's Smooth Radio|publisher=Radio Today |date=8 January 2014|accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref>\n*9 January \u2013 [[Blur (band)|Blur]] drummer [[Dave Rowntree]] begins hosting a Thursday evening show for [[XFM]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/blurs-drummer-dave-rowntree-to-join-xfm/ |title=Blur\u2019s drummer Dave Rowntree to join Xfm |publisher=Radio Today |date=8 January 2014 |accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref>\n*10 January \u2013 Liverpool-based stations [[City Talk 105.9]] and [[Radio City 96.7]] both broadcast exclusive interviews with Prime Minister [[David Cameron]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/pm-david-cameron-interviewed-on-city-talk/ |title=PM David Cameron interviewed on City Talk |publisher=Radio Today |date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref>\n*10 January \u2013 [[BBC Radio 1|Radio 1]] announces a schedule change that will see weekend breakfast presenter [[Gemma Cairney]] and weekday early breakfast host [[Devin Griffin|Dev]] swap shows.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/media/news/a542955/bbc-radio-1s-gemma-cairney-to-swap-shows-with-dev.html |title=BBC Radio 1's Gemma Cairney to swap shows with Dev |publisher=Digital Spy |date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref>\n*14 January \u2013 [[talkSPORT]] secures a deal with the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' to produce content featuring sports journalists and writers from the newspaper, including [[Jamie Redknapp]], [[Martin Keown]] and [[Graham Poll]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/talksport-does-a-deal-with-the-daily-mail/ |title=talkSPORT does a deal with the Daily Mail |publisher=Radio Today |date=14 January 2014 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n*16 January \u2013 [[BBC Radio Northampton]] Breakfast Show presenter Stuart Linnell receives hospital treatment after he is hit by a police car shortly before he is due to go on air.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/bbc-radio-presenter-hit-by-a-police-car/ |title=BBC radio presenter hit by a police car |publisher=Radio Today |date=16 January 2014 |accessdate=16 January 2014}}</ref>\n*19 January \u2013 [[BBC Radio 1|Radio 1]]'s [[YouTube]] channel attracts its one millionth subscriber.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/bbc-radio-1-celebrates-1-million-youtubers/ |title=BBC Radio 1 celebrates 1 million YouTubers |publisher=Radio Today |date=27 January 2014 |accessdate=27 January 2014}}</ref>\n*20 January \u2013 [[Global Radio]] is found to be in breach of their license remit for [[Heart Cornwall]] after a listener complained to [[OfCom]] that there was not enough local news and speech to make it a fully local station.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/global-radio-in-breach-for-heart-cornwall/ |title=Global Radio in breach for Heart Cornwall |publisher=Radio Today |date=20 January 2014 |accessdate=27 January 2014}}</ref>\n*24 January \u2013 [[Heart London]] presenters [[Jamie Theakston]] and [[Emma Bunton]] present their breakfast show from a listener's house in Buckinghamshire as part of a [[Sky (UK and Ireland)|Sky]] promotion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/jamie-emma-go-live-from-buckinghamshire/ |title=Jamie & Emma go live from Buckinghamshire |publisher=Radio Today |date=27 January 2014 |accessdate=27 January 2014}}</ref>\n*29 January \u2013 [[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]] presenter [[John Suchet]] opens The Classic FM Foundation Lecture Room at the headquarters of London-based music therapy charity [[Nordoff Robbins]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/john-suchet-opens-classic-fm-lecture-room/ |title=John Suchet opens Classic FM Lecture Room |publisher=Radio Today |date=29 January 2014 |accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n*29 January \u2013 [[Free Radio (network)|Free Radio]] announces that [[Pat Sharp]] will present a special edition of its ''Guess the Year'' show for a week in February, his first on air appearance since leaving [[Smooth Radio]] in December 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/pat-sharp-to-appear-on-free-radio-breakfast/ |title=Pat Sharp to appear on Free Radio breakfast |publisher=Radio Today |date=29 January 2014 |accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>\n*31 January \u2013 [[BBC Radio 4]] decides to \"rest\" the ''[[The Archers|Archers]]'' spin-off ''Ambridge Extra'', which has been on air since 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25977549 |title=Archers bosses 'rest' Ambridge Extra spin-off |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=31 January 2014 |accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n*4 February \u2013 The ''[[Radio Today (website)|Radio Today]]'' website reports that [[Ofcom]] have given [[Global Radio]] permission to remove [[Smooth Radio]] from the [[Digital One]] platform, and replace it with a new national station. Under the agreement, Smooth will continue to air on its regional FM frequencies, but with a greater local output.<ref name=Radio-Today-2014-02-04>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/02/smooth-radio-to-be-removed-from-digital-1/ |title=Smooth Radio to be removed from Digital 1 |publisher=Radio Today |date=4 February 2014 |accessdate=5 February 2014}}</ref>\n*6 February \u2013 Global Radio sells eight of its regional stations to Irish media holdings firm [[Communicorp]].<ref name=Radio-Today-2014-02-06>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/02/communicorp-buys-8-global-radio-stations/ |title=Communicorp buys 8 Global Radio stations |publisher=Radio Today |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref>\n*11 February \u2013 [[LBC 97.3]] launches nationally on the [[Digital One]] platform, taking over the slot formerly occupied by Jazz FM. The station also secures a sponsorship deal with the ''[[Financial Times]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/global-radio-to-take-lbc-national-on-d1/ |title=Global Radio to take LBC national on D1 |publisher=Radio Today |date=30 January 2014 |accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/02/financial-times-sponsors-new-uk-wide-lbc/ |title=Financial Times sponsors new UK wide LBC |publisher=Radio Today |date=11 February 2014 |accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref>\n*13 February \u2013 Disc jockey [[Dave Lee Travis]] is found not guilty on 12 accounts of historical sexual offences following a trial at [[Southwark Crown Court]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-26177136 |work=BBC News |title=Dave Lee Travis trial: DJ cleared of indecent assault |publisher=BBC |date=13 February 2014 |accessdate=13 February 2014}}</ref> However, after the jury could not reach a decision on another two charges, it is announced on 24 February that he will face a retrial on the remaining allegations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-26322552|title=Dave Lee Travis to face retrial on sex offence charges|publisher=BBC|work=BBC News|date=24 February 2014|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> On 28 March, it is announced he will face charges on another count.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-26787306 |work=BBC News |title=Dave Lee Travis to be charged with indecent assault |publisher=BBC |date=28 March 2014 |accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref>\n*14 February \u2013 Free Radio hosts a wedding for two dogs to mark [[Valentine's Day]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Martin |first=Roy |url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/02/valentines-day-dog-stunt-at-free-radio/ |title=Valentine\u2019s Day dog stunt at Free Radio |publisher=Radio Today |date=14 February 2014 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref>\n*17 February \u2013 Speaking at the Radio Academy, Head of Music at Radio 1, George Ergatoudis, says that [[streaming media|streaming]] will be included in the top 40 singles chart.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/02/streaming-to-be-included-in-singles-chart/ |title=Streaming to be included in singles chart |publisher=Radio Today |date=19 February 2014 |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n*24 February \u2013 Plans are announced for Smooth Radio's relaunch, which will begin from 3 March. The changes will see the departure of several presenters, including [[Simon Bates]] and [[Lynn Parsons]], while [[Andrew Castle]], [[Kate Garraway]] and [[Myleene Klass]] will join the lineup. Castle will be the station's new breakfast presenter in London, while Garraway will take over Parsons' mid-morning show. Klass will present a weekend show.<ref name=Radio-Today-2014-02-24>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/02/bates-and-parsons-out-as-smooth-relaunches/ |title=Bates and Parsons out as Smooth relaunches |publisher=Radio Today |date=24 February 2014 |accessdate=24 February 2014}}</ref>\n*25 February \u2013 Community station The Cat is awarded a five-year licence by Ofcom to broadcast to [[Nentwich]] and [[Crewe]] in [[Cheshire]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/02/the-cat-catches-five-year-ofcom-licence/ |title=The Cat catches five year Ofcom licence |publisher=Radio Today |date=25 February 2014 |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n*3 March \u2013 \n**Radio 1 presenter [[Nick Grimshaw]] leaves his breakfast show early to attend hospital for an [[X-ray]] after swallowing glass while drinking a cup of coffee. [[Fearne Cotton]] presents the remainder of the programme, while Grimshaw is discharged following treatment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/26416948 |title=Nick Grimshaw leaves Radio 1 show after swallowing glass |publisher=BBC |work=Newsbeat |date=3 March 2014 |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n**''Radio Today'' reports that [[London Turkish Radio]] is in serious continuous breach of its Ofcom licence after it ceased broadcasting following a power cut in October 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/03/ltr-ceases-broadcasting-after-power-cut/ |title=LTR ceases broadcasting after power cut |publisher=Radio Today |date=3 March 2014 |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n**A \"technical error\" leads to sound effects being broadcast over a news item about the trial of South African Olympic athlete [[Oscar Pistorius]] on [[BBC Coventry & Warwickshire]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/03/bbc-says-sorry-for-local-radio-news-fail/ |title=BBC says sorry for local radio news fail |publisher=Radio Today |date=5 March 2014 |accessdate=5 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Dugald |last=Baird |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/mar/05/bbc-apologises-playing-screams-and-howling-oscar-pistorius-report |title=BBC apologises after playing screams and howling over Oscar Pistorius report |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=5 March 2014 |accessdate=5 March 2014}}</ref>\n*5 March \u2013 [[Mark Lawson]] will step down as presenter of Radio 4's ''[[Front Row (radio programme)|Front Row]]'' after 16 years, it is announced.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26451155 |work=BBC News |title=Mark Lawson to leave BBC's Front Row |publisher=BBC |date=5 March 2014 |accessdate=5 March 2014}}</ref>\n*7\u20138 March \u2013 [[BBC Radio 1|Radio 1]] marks [[International Women's Day]] with two nights of an all-female line-up from 7{{nbsp}}pm to 7{{nbsp}}am, featuring presenters like [[Annie Nightingale]] and [[Adele Roberts]]. The second night is also aired on [[BBC Radio 1Xtra|1Xtra]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/01/radio-1-1xtra-go-all-female-all-night/ |title=Radio 1 & 1Xtra go all female all night |publisher=Radio Today |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>\n*12 March \u2013 ''[[Sky News]]'' host [[Kay Burley]] will join ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]''{{'}}s [[Stig Abell]] to host a Sunday morning magazine programme for LBC from 23 March.<ref>{{cite news|last=Greenslade |first=Roy |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2014/mar/12/kay-burley-stephen-abell |title=Kay Burley and The Sun's Stig Abell to co-host LBC breakfast radio show |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=12 August 2014 |accessdate=13 March 2014}}</ref>\n*14 March \u2013 Global Radio announces that Gold will become a non-stop music service, with the exception of the breakfast show and Saturday's ''Vinyl Heaven''. Presenters Paul Coyte, Eamonn Kelly, Dean Martin and [[Andy Peebles]] are also dropped from the network.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/03/gold-drops-presenters-outside-breakfast/ |title=Gold drops presenters outside breakfast |publisher=Radio Today |date=14 March 2014 |accessdate=15 March 2014}}</ref>\n*15 March \u2013 Singer [[Lily Allen]] guest presents [[Dermot O'Leary]]'s Saturday show on [[BBC Radio 2]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/03/lily-allen-to-cover-dermots-radio-2-show/ |title=Lily Allen to cover Dermot\u2019s Radio 2 show |publisher=Radio Today |date=13 March 2014 |accessdate=13 March 2014}}</ref>\n*18 March \u2013 In an interview with [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]'s [[Richard Bacon (broadcaster)|Richard Bacon]], former Radio 1 presenter [[Noel Edmonds]] talks of his desire to buy the BBC and turn it into a not-for-profit broadcaster, while scrapping [[BBC Local Radio]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/03/drop-bbc-local-radio-says-noel-edmonds/ |title=\"Cut BBC Local Radio\" says Noel Edmonds |publisher=Radio Today |date=18 March 2014 |accessdate=18 March 2014}}</ref>\n*18 March \u2013 [[BBC Radio Sussex]] and [[BBC Radio Surrey]] have hired [[David Jensen]], [[David Hamilton (broadcaster)|David Hamilton]] and [[Jeni Barnett]] to cover some of their shows in March and April.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/03/kid-jensen-joins-bbc-sussex-and-surrey/ |title=Kid Jensen joins BBC Sussex and Surrey |publisher=Radio Today |date=18 March 2014 |accessdate=18 March 2014}}</ref>\n*21 March \u2013 Cyclist Sir [[Bradley Wiggins]] makes a cameo appearance in Radio 4's ''[[The Archers]]'' as part of the BBC's [[Sport Relief]] celebrations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26557864 |work=BBC News |title=Sir Bradley Wiggins set for Archers cameo appearance |publisher=BBC |date=13 March 2014 |accessdate=13 March 2014}}</ref>\n*24 March \u2013 \n**Smooth Radio  returns to airing local output on its regional frequencies, with local programming for Breakfast and Drivetime, and a raft of [[Smooth Radio presenter history|new presenters]] joining the network.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/03/smooth-radio-returns-to-regional-output/ |title=Smooth Radio returns to regional output |publisher=Radio Today |date=19 March 2014 |accessdate=19 March 2014}}</ref>\n**Smooth Radio replaces [[Gold (radio)|Gold]] on MW across southern England.<ref>[https://www.a516digital.com/2014/02/gold-announces-am-and-dab-departure-date.html Gold announces AM and DAB departure date]</ref>\n*26 March \u2013 LBC airs a studio debate between [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Deputy Prime Minister]] [[Nick Clegg]] and [[UK Independence Party]] leader [[Nigel Farrage]] discussing Britain's future in Europe ahead of [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|May's elections]] to the European Parliament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/03/lbc-to-host-first-leaders-europe-debate/ |title=LBC to host first leaders\u2019 Europe debate |publisher=Radio Today |date=5 March 2014 |accessdate=5 March 2014}}</ref>\n*28 March \u2013 [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] celebrates its 20th anniversary.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26766698 |work=BBC News |title=Radio 5 live celebrates 20 years of broadcasting |publisher=BBC |date=28 March 2014 |accessdate=28 March 2014}}</ref>\n*30 March \u2013 More than 600 editions of [[Alistair Cooke]]'s ''[[Letter from America]]'' from the 1970s, thought to have been lost, are recovered from cassette recordings made by two listeners.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Connell |first=Paddy |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-26692193 |work=BBC News |title=Alistair Cooke: Long-lost letters from 1970s America |publisher=BBC |date=30 March 2014 |accessdate=30 March 2014}}</ref>\n*31 March \u2013 [[Radio Caroline North]] returns for a month to celebrate its 50th birthday, broadcasting from a lightship in [[Liverpool]]'s [[Albert Dock, Liverpool|Albert Dock]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/02/caroline-north-returns-for-50th-birthday/ |title=Caroline North returns for 50th birthday |publisher=Radio Today |date=19 February 2014 |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n*1 April \u2013 [[Insight Radio]] launches on [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]] channel 730.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/04/rnib-insight-radio-launches-on-freeview/ |title=RNIB Insight Radio launches on Freeview |publisher=Radio Today |date=3 April 2014 |accessdate=7 April 2014}}</ref>\n*4 April \u2013 [[Real XS Glasgow]] closes at midnight, and is rebranded as [[Xfm Scotland]] from 7 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/04/this-is-the-last-link-on-real-xs-glasgow/ |title=This is the last link on Real XS Glasgow |publisher=Radio Today |date=6 April 2014 |accessdate=7 April 2014}}</ref>\n*6 April \u2013 Smooth Radio launches a multi-million ad campaign featuring [[Michael Bubl\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/04/smooth-radios-new-multi-million-campaign/ |title=Smooth Radio\u2019s new multi-million campaign |publisher=Radio Today |date=6 April 2014 |accessdate=7 April 2014}}</ref>\n*7\u201310 April \u2013 As part of the BBC's celebration of the 20th anniversary of [[Britpop]], [[Steve Lamacq]] and [[Jo Whiley]] present a week of Radio 1's long running ''[[The Evening Session]]'' on [[BBC Radio 2]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/03/lamacq-whiley-reunited-on-bbc-radio-2/ |title=Lamacq & Whiley reunited on BBC Radio 2 |publisher=Radio Today |date=17 March 2014 |accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref>\n*9 April \u2013 [[Sajid Javid]] is appointed as [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport|Culture Secretary]] following the resignation of [[Maria Miller]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Andrew |last=Grice |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/culture-secretary-maria-miller-resigns-amid-expenses-row-9247795.html |title=Maria Miller resigns: Sajid Javid appointed new Culture Secretary following expenses row |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=9 April 2014 |accessdate=9 April 2014}}</ref>\n*15 April \u2013 [[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]] dedicates an entire 24 hours of its music to the recordings of Sir [[Neville Marriner]] to celebrate his 90th birthday.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/02/classic-fm-to-air-one-conductor-for-24hr/ |title=Classic FM to air one conductor for 24hr |publisher=Radio Today |date=26 February 2014 |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n*1 May \u2013 The BBC will provide radio, television and online coverage of the [[Hay Literary Festival]] in June, it is announced, as it takes over broadcast rights for the event from [[Sky Arts]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-mid-wales-27244052 |work=BBC News |title=BBC to broadcast Hay Festival on radio, TV, and online |publisher=BBC |date=1 May 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref>\n*6 May \u2013 \n**Real Radio is rebranded as Heart.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/05/heart-arrives-in-former-real-radio-areas/ |title=Heart arrives in former Real Radio areas |publisher=Radio Today |date=6 May 2014 |accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref>\n**Following the launch of [[Heart North Wales]], [[Capital North West and Wales]] replaces the former Heart station Heart North Wales & West which had broadcast to [[Cheshire]], the [[Wirral Peninsula]] and [[North Wales]].<ref>[http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/04/global-confirms-heart-expansion-details/ Global confirms Heart expansion details], RadioToday, 14 April 2014</ref>\n*9 May \u2013 [[BBC Radio Manchester]] and [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] are taken off air when fire alarms are activated at the BBC's Salford studios.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/05/bbc-radio-stations-in-salford-evacuated/ |title=BBC radio stations in Salford evacuated |publisher=Radio Today |date=9 May 2014 |accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref>\n*11 May \u2013 [[BBC Radio Devon]] presenter David Lowe has lost his \"Singers and Swingers\" slot after playing a 1932 version of \"[[The Sun Has Got His Hat On]]\" by [[Ambrose & His Orchestra]] that includes the [[nigger|n-word]], it is reported.<ref name=Independent-2014-05-11>{{cite news|first=Maev |last=Kennedy |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/may/11/bbc-dj-david-lowe-quits-racism-row-jeremy-clarkson |title=BBC DJ David Lowe quits in latest racism row |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 May 2014 |accessdate=11 May 2014}}</ref> Lowe, who had not realised the song contained the word, offered to give an on-air apology or \"fall on [his] sword\" after a viewer complained, the latter of which was accepted.<ref>{{cite news|first=Steve |last=Anderson |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/tv-radio/after-jeremy-clarkson-row-veteran-dj-is-forced-to-quit-for-accidentally-playing-song-with-nword-in-9349709.html |title=Jeremy Clarkson row: Veteran DJ David Lowe 'forced to quit' for accidentally playing song with 'N-word' |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=11 May 2014 |accessdate=11 May 2014}}</ref> The BBC says the incident could have been handled better.<ref name=BBC-2014-05-11/> Lowe was offered his job back, but declined citing stress over the incident.<ref name=BBC-2014-05-11>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-27360884 |work=BBC News |title=BBC Radio Devon DJ David Lowe loses job over racist word |publisher=BBC |date=11 May 2014 |accessdate=11 May 2014}}</ref> The incident follows recent controversy over [[Jeremy Clarkson]]'s use of the same word while recording an episode of ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'', which led to him receiving a final warning from the Corporation.<ref name=Independent-2014-05-11/>\n*16 May \u2013 An [[LBC]] interview with [[UK Independence Party]] leader [[Nigel Farage]] is interrupted by his spin doctor, [[Patrick O'Flynn]] after the latter believed it had overrun. During the interview Farage was questioned about comments he made concerning his discomfort with hearing foreign languages spoken in the UK given that his wife is German, and whether he would sign his party up to an expenses audit process.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27437982 |work=BBC News |title=Nigel Farage's spin doctor interrupts live radio interview |publisher=BBC |date=16 May 2014 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===June===\n*13 June \u2013 [[Stephanie Hirst]] hosts the final edition of [[Hirsty's Daily Dose]] on [[Capital Yorkshire]] after 11\u00bd years.\n\n===July===\n*1 July \u2013 [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] announces the departure of [[Richard Bacon (broadcaster)|Richard Bacon]], [[Victoria Derbyshire]] and [[Shelagh Fogarty]], who will leave when the station's schedule is overhauled in the autumn.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28105640 |title=Richard Bacon and Victoria Derbyshire to leave 5 live |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=1 July 2014 |accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref>\n*7 July \u2013 [[Emma Barnett]], women's editor of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' will join BBC Radio 5 Live.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28199152 |title=Emma Barnett, Telegraph's woman's editor, joins 5 live |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=7 July 2014 |accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref>\n*25 July \u2013 Actress [[Eleanor Bron]] has joined ''[[The Archers]]'' as Carol Tregorran, a character who last appeared in the series 60 years ago, BBC News reports.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28472190 |work=BBC News |title=Eleanor Bron joins The Archers cast |publisher=BBC |date=25 July 2014 |accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===August===\n*15 August \u2013 [[Jonathan Ross]] will return to BBC Radio 2 for the first time in four years when he sits in for [[Steve Wright (DJ)|Steve Wright]] from 26 to 29 August.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28801915 |work=BBC News |title=Jonathan Ross returns to BBC Radio 2 |publisher=BBC |date=15 August 2014 |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n*1 September \u2013 [[Peter Horrocks]] will step down as Director of the [[BBC World Service]] and leave the Corporation in early 2015, it is announces.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29009119 |title=BBC World Service boss Peter Horrocks to step down |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=1 September 2014 |accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref>\n*15 September \u2013 The [[Jazz FM (UK)|Jazz FM]] schedule receives an overhaul, which includes an hour of specialist jazz programmes each day, and [[Lynn Parsons]] taking over as presenter of ''The Jazz Breakfast''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/09/lynn-parsons-to-host-jazz-fm-breakfast/|title=Lynn Parsons to host Jazz FM Breakfast|work=Radio Today|date=11 September 2014|accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref>\n*29 September \u2013 [[Sky Sports News Radio]] has ceased broadcasting, it is reported, its content having been subsumed into Sky Sports.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29407848|title=Sky Sports News Radio service closes down|publisher=BBC|date=29 September 2014|work=BBC News|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n*6 October \u2013 Schedule changes at [[BBC Radio Five Live]] are rolled out, and see [[Adrian Chiles]] take on the mid morning show, and [[Dan Walker (sports journalist)|Dan Walker]] and Sarah Brett taking on afternoons.<ref>{{cite news|first=Pete |last=Naughton |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/11147296/Why-wont-Radio-5-Live-let-a-woman-run-the-show.html |title=Why won\u2019t Radio 5 Live let a woman run the show? |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=7 October 2014 |accessdate=17 November 2014}}</ref>\n*11 October \u2013 During an interview on [[BBC Radio Five Live]] with [[Stephen Nolan]], [[Stephanie Hirst]] reveals she is in the process of gender transition from male to female. This being one of the reasons why she left her show [[Hirsty's Daily Dose]] on [[Capital Yorkshire]] earlier in 2014.\n*15 October \u2013 Launch of the [[BBC Genome|BBC Genome Project]], an online resource allowing users to browse through back copies of the ''[[Radio Times]]'' from 1923 to 2009, including television and radio listings.<ref name=\"Hilbish\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/aboutthebbc/posts/Genome-The-Radio-Times-Archive-is-now-live|title=Genome \u2013 Radio Times archive now live|last=Bishop|first=Hilary|work=BBC Online|publisher=BBC|date=15 October 2014|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/oct/16/bbc-digitises-radio-times-back-issues-genome-project|title=BBC digitises Radio Times back issues|first=Mark|last=Sweney|newspaper=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|date=16 October 2014|accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref>\n*20 October \u2013 Ofcom reprimands BBC Radio 1 for breaking the broadcasting guidelines after [[Lily Allen]] and [[Ed Sheeran]] swore on air during the Big Weekend festival in May.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29691358|title=BBC Radio 1's Lily Allen set broke swearing rules|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=20 October 2014|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref>\n*22 October \u2013 Former Radio 1 presenter [[Mike Read]] requests the withdrawal of \"[[UKIP Calypso]]\", a song he wrote in support of the [[UK Independence Party]] after complaints that it was racist. The song featured Read singing in praise of the party using a fake Caribbean accent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29722860|title=Mike Read withdraws UKIP Calypso song|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=22 October 2014|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref>\n*22 October \u2013 The BBC issues an apology after [[Michael Buerk]] criticised the victim in the [[R v Evans and McDonald|Ched Evans rape case]] during a trailer for the evening's edition of Radio 4's ''[[The Moral Maze]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/oct/22/bbc-apologises-michael-buerk-ched-evans-radio-4|title=BBC apologises over Michael Buerk\u2019s comments on Ched Evans case|newspaper=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Media Group|date=22 October 2014|accessdate=23 October 2014}}</ref>\n*27 October \u2013 [[Richard Allinson]] joins [[Magic 105.4 FM]] to present the weekday drive-time show.\n\n===November===\n*7 November \u2013 The [[Radio Academy]] announces the discontinuation of its annual [[Radio Academy Awards]] after three decades. The Awards had been sponsored by [[Sony plc|Sony]] until 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29956456 |title=Radio Academy scraps annual awards |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=7 November 2014 |accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n*10 November \u2013 BBC Radio 1 is censured by Ofcom after an edition of its ''[[Newsbeat]]'' programme aired in June that included an interview with a British-born [[jihadism|jihadist]] in which he compared his membership of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] to the video game ''[[Call of Duty]]''. The regulator felt the comments had no context.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29987119 |title=BBC's Newsbeat censured over Islamic State news report |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=10 November 2014 |accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n*14 November \u2013 \n**[[World War II]] [[Royal Navy]] test pilot [[Eric Brown (pilot)|Eric \"Winkle\" Brown]] appears as a guest on the 3000th edition of ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Winkle-3-000th-Desert-Island-Discs-castaway/story-24409007-detail/story.html |title='Winkle' becomes 3,000th Desert Island Discs castaway |publisher=Local World |newspaper=Western Morning News |date=November 2014 |accessdate=11 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111173852/http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Winkle-3-000th-Desert-Island-Discs-castaway/story-24409007-detail/story.html |archive-date=11 November 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n**Former BBC DJ [[Chris Denning]] pleads guilty to further sexual abuse of boys aged nine to sixteen during the 1970s and 1980s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-30058689 |title=Chris Denning convicted again of sex abuse against boys |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=14 November 2014 |accessdate=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n*15 November \u2013 [[Smooth Radio|Smooth Christmas]] returns to DAB in preparation for the launch of a new station with the Smooth brand.<ref name=Radio-Today-2014-11-10>{{cite news|first=Roy |last=Martin |url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/11/global-to-launch-smooth-extra-on-national-dab/ |title=Global to launch Smooth Extra on national DAB |publisher=Radio Today |date=10 November 2014 |accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref>\n*19 November \u2013 [[BBC Radio Norfolk]] presenter Nick Conrad apologises following comments he made about rape during a live debate about footballer and convicted rapist [[Ched Evans]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-norfolk-30112715|title=BBC presenter Nick Conrad sorry for Ched Evans rape remarks |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=19 November 2014 |accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n*20 November \u2013 [[Vanessa Feltz]], [[Jo Whiley]], [[Trevor Nelson]] and [[Nicky Campbell]] are among several presenters to be inducted into the Radio Academy Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-30129929|title=Vanessa Feltz to be inducted into Radio Academy Hall of Fame|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=20 November 2014|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref>\n*27 November \u2013 BBC Radio 4 will air a 10-hour adaptation of [[Leo Tolstoy]]'s ''[[War and Peace]]'' on New Year's Day 2015, the BBC confirms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30228501 |title=War and Peace to take over Radio 4 |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=27 November 2014 |accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref>\n*28 November \u2013 Guest editors are announced for BBC Radio 4's ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|The Today Programme]]'' over the festive season. They will include comedian [[Lenny Henry]], House of Commons Speaker [[John Bercow]] and [[Mervyn King (economist)|Mervyn King]], the former Governor of the Bank of England.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30243337 |title=Lenny Henry to guest edit Radio 4's Today |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=29 November 2014 |accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref>\n*30 November \u2013 The online classic hits station [[Solid Gold Gem]] ceases broadcasting after two years on air.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/11/online-station-solid-gold-gem-am-closes-after-two-years/ |title=Online station Solid Gold GEM AM closes after two years |publisher=Radio Today |date=27 November 2014 |accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n*2 December \u2013 [[BBC Radio Devon]] announces that [[Simon Bates]] will join the station to present the breakfast show from January 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/simon-bates-radio-devon |title=BBC Radio Devon announces Simon Bates as new Breakfast presenter from 12 January |publisher=BBC |work=BBC Media Centre |date=2 December 2014 |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref>\n*7 December \u2013 Comedian [[Tom Binns]] apologises to his wife, radio producer Liesl Soards, after he read out the contents of an email exchange she had with Simon Bates while the two were working at Smooth Radio, then described Bates as being \"as focused as a cunt\". Binns had been commenting on Bates forthcoming Radio Devon show.<ref>{{cite news|first=Roy |last=Martin |url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/12/tom-binns-apologies-for-comments-about-simon-bates/ |title=Tom Binns apologises for comments about Simon Bates |publisher=Radio Today |date=7 December 2014 |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref>\n*15 December \u2013 Solid Gold Gem is relaunched with Len Groat as its new manager after closing down two weeks earlier. No reason is given for the hiatus.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/12/online-oldies-station-solid-gold-gem-am-returns/ |title=Online oldies station Solid Gold Gem AM returns |publisher=Radio Today |date=7 December 2014 |accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> \n*27 December \u2013 Launch of [[Smooth Extra]] on DAB.<ref name=Radio-Today-2014-12-27/>\n*30 December \u2013 Papers released by the National Archives reveal that in September 1979 [[Margaret Thatcher]] considered introducing advertising for some BBC radio services, but later scrapped the idea after encountering opposition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-30622889 |title=Margaret Thatcher considered advertising on BBC |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=30 December 2014 |accessdate=30 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Station debuts==\n*7 April \u2013 [[Xfm Scotland]]\n*27 December \u2013 [[Smooth Radio|Smooth Extra]]<ref name=Radio-Today-2014-12-27>{{cite news|first=Roy |last=Martin |url=http://radiotoday.co.uk/2014/12/smooth-extra-launches-on-dab-digital-radio/ |title=Smooth Extra launches on DAB digital radio |publisher=Radio Today |date=27 December 2014 |accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Relaunching this year after a break of one month or more==\n*15 November \u2013 Smooth Christmas (2011, 2012, '''2014''')\n\n==Closing this year==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \"\n! Date || Station || Debut(s)\n|-\n|4 April\n|[[Real XS Glasgow]]\n|2007\n|-\n|27 December\n|Smooth Christmas\n|2011, 2012, 2014\n|}\n\n==Programme debuts==\n* 4 August \u2013 ''[[Home Front (BBC radio series)|Home Front]]'' on [[BBC Radio 4]] (2014\u2013Present)\n* 10 October \u2013 ''[[Friday Sports Panel]]'' on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] (2014\u2013Present)\n\n==Returning this year after a break of one year or longer==\n* 30 July \u2013 ''[[Dead Ringers (comedy)|Dead Ringers]]'' returning to [[BBC Radio 4]] (2000\u20132007, '''2014\u2013Present''')\n\n==Continuing programmes==\n===1940s===\n* ''[[The Sunday Hour]]'' (1940\u20132018)\n* ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' (1942\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Woman's Hour]]'' (1946\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Book at Bedtime|A Book at Bedtime]]'' (1949\u2013Present)\n\n===1950s===\n* ''[[The Archers]]'' (1950\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|The Today Programme]]'' (1957\u2013Present)\n\n===1960s===\n* ''[[Farming Today]]'' (1960\u2013Present)\n* ''[[The World at One]]'' (1965\u2013Present)\n* ''[[The Official Chart]]'' (1967\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Just a Minute]]'' (1967\u2013Present)\n* ''[[The Living World]]'' (1968\u2013Present)\n* ''[[The Organist Entertains]]'' (1969\u20132018)\n\n===1970s===\n* ''[[PM (BBC Radio 4)|PM]]'' (1970\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Start the Week]]'' (1970\u2013Present)\n* ''[[You and Yours]]'' (1970\u2013Present)\n* ''[[I'm Sorry I Haven't a Clue]]'' (1972\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Good Morning Scotland]]'' (1973\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Newsbeat]]'' (1973\u2013Present)\n* ''[[File on 4]]'' (1977\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Money Box]]'' (1977\u2013Present)\n* ''[[The News Quiz]]'' (1977\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Feedback (radio series)|Feedback]]'' (1979\u2013Present)\n* ''[[The Food Programme]]'' (1979\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Science in Action (radio programme)|Science in Action]]'' (1979\u2013Present)\n\n===1980s===\n* ''[[Steve Wright in the Afternoon]]'' (1981\u20131993, '''1999\u2013Present''')\n* ''[[In Business]]'' (1983\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Sounds of the 60s]]'' (1983\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Loose Ends (radio)|Loose Ends]] (1986\u2013Present)\n\n===1990s===\n* ''[[The Moral Maze]]'' (1990\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Essential Selection]]'' (1991\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Essential Mix]]'' (1993\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Up All Night (radio show)|Up All Night]]'' (1994\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Wake Up to Money]]'' (1994\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Private Passions]]'' (1995\u2013Present)\n* ''[[In Our Time (radio series)|In Our Time]]'' (1998\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Material World (radio programme)|Material World]]'' (1998\u2013Present)\n* ''[[Scott Mills (radio show)|Scott Mills]]'' (1998\u2013Present)\n* ''[[The Now Show]] (1998\u2013Present)\n\n===2000s===\n* ''[[