le=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|204.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Mario Cipollini]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |18 July || [[Meyrignac-l'\u00c9glise]] to [[Corr\u00e8ze]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|58|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] || {{flagathlete|[[Jan Ullrich]]|GER}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |19 July || [[Brive-la-Gaillarde]] to [[Montauban]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|190.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Jacky Durand]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |20 July || [[Montauban]] to [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|210|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[L\u00e9on van Bon]]|NED}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |21 July || [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]] to [[Luchon]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|196.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || High mountain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Rodolfo Massi]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |22 July || [[Luchon]] to [[Plateau de Beille]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|170|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || High mountain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Marco Pantani]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 23 July\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Ari\u00e8ge (department)|Ari\u00e8ge]]\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" | Rest day\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 12|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |24 July || [[Tarascon-sur-Ari\u00e8ge]] to [[Cap d'Agde]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|190|km|0|abbr=on}}{{efn|Stage 12 was originally scheduled to be {{convert|206|km|mi|abbr=on}} long, but as a result of the delayed start due to a riders' strike, the stage was shortened to {{convert|190|km|0|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=142}}}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Tom Steels]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |25 July || [[Frontignan la Peyrade]] to [[Carpentras]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|196|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Daniele Nardello]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 14|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |26 July || [[Valr\u00e9as]] to [[Grenoble]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|186.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mediummountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Mountain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Stuart O'Grady]]|AUS}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 15|15]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |27 July || [[Grenoble]] to [[Les Deux Alpes]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|189|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || High mountain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Marco Pantani]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 16|16]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |28 July || [[Vizille]] to [[Albertville]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|204|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || High mountain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Jan Ullrich]]|GER}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 17|17]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |29 July || [[Albertville]] to [[Aix-les-Bains]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|149|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || High mountain stage || style=\"text-align:center;\" | \u2014{{efn|name=\"note-stage-17\"|Stage 17 was cancelled and did not count as the riders held a strike due to the developing [[Festina affair]].<ref name=\"letour-stage-17\">{{cite web|title=Stage 17 cancelled|url=http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/|website=[[Tour de France]]|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=24 March 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990203085256/http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/|archivedate=3 February 1999}}</ref>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 18|18]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |30 July || [[Aix-les-Bains]] to [[Neuch\u00e2tel]] (Switzerland)|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|218.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mediummountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Mountain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Tom Steels]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 19|19]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |31 July || [[La Chaux-de-Fonds]] (Switzerland) to [[Autun]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|242|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Magnus B\u00e4ckstedt]]|SWE}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 20|20]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1 August || [[Montceau-les-Mines]] to [[Le Creusot]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|52|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Time Trial.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || [[Individual time trial]] || {{flagathlete|[[Jan Ullrich]]|GER}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 21|21]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2 August || [[Melun]] to [[Paris]] ([[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es stage in the Tour de France|Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]])|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|147.5|km|0|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Flat stage || {{flagathlete|[[Tom Steels]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|3875|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=89}}\n|}\n\n==Race overview==\n{{main|1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11|1998 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21}}\n\n===Pre-Tour revelations===\nOn 4 March 1998, a truck belonging to the Dutch {{ct|TVM|1998|nolink=yes}} team had been seized by [[customs officer]]s in [[Reims]], France, revealing 104 vials of recombinant [[erythropoietin]] (EPO), a drug with performance-enhancing effects. The two [[Bicycle mechanic|mechanics]] in the truck were released and the vials were taken by the police, who said they had more \"important matters\" to be concerned with.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=2}}{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=12}} During the [[1998 Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]], a race held two weeks before the start of the Tour, [[Christophe Moreau]] of Festina tested positive for the anabolic steroid [[mesterolone]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9: De las Cuevas leader |url=https://www.ladepeche.fr/article/1998/06/11/185857-dauphine-libere-de-las-cuevas-leader.html |accessdate=16 August 2019 |work=[[La D\u00e9p\u00eache du Midi]] |date=11 June 1998 |language=French}}</ref> The UCI accepted Festina's explanation that the positive test was a result of the influence of a team masseur, and Moreau was allowed to start the Tour de France.{{sfn|Woodland|2003|p=155}}\n\nThree days before the start of the Tour, on 8 July, [[Willy Voet]], a ''[[soigneur]]'' (team assistant) with the Festina squad, was stopped by customs officers driving along a back road on the [[Belgium\u2013France border|Franco\u2013Belgian border]].{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=1}} A routine check revealed that he carried a large quantity of performance-enhancing drugs with him.{{efn|The content of Voet's car was \"82 vials of Saizen ([[somatropin]], or [[human growth hormone]]), 60 capsules of [[Pantestone]] ([[epitestosterone]]), 248 vials of physiological serum, 8 pre-filled syringes containing hepatitis-A vaccine, 2 boxes of 30 Hyperlipen tablets (to lower the amount of fat in the blood), 4 further doses of somatropin, 4 ampoules of Synacthene (to increase the rate at which [[Corticosteroid|corticoid hormones]] are secreted by the adrenal gland) and 2 vials of [[amphetamine]]\" as well as \"234 doses of recombinant human [[erythropoietin]]\".{{sfn|Rendell|2007|p=117}}}} He was thereafter placed under arrest, initially claiming they were \"for personal use\".{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=1}} The following day, police carried out a search of Festina's headquarters in [[Meyzieu]], close to Lyon.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=19}} On the day before the prologue, a judicial inquiry was opened by the public prosecutor's office and Voet was held for investigation,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=19}} with the story also breaking to the media.{{sfn|Rendell|2007|p=117}} The Tour's organisation as well as Festina were quick to dismiss the news as having nothing to do with the race.<ref name=\"nytimes_prol\">{{cite news |last=Abt |first=Samuel |author-link=Samuel Abt |title=Cycling; Boardman wins as drug case arises |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/12/sports/cycling-boardman-wins-as-drug-case-arises.html |accessdate=12 May 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=12 July 1998|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512122629/https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/12/sports/cycling-boardman-wins-as-drug-case-arises.html|archivedate=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2008|p=246}}\n\n===Early stages in Ireland===\n[[File:1998 Tour de France, Prologue map.png|thumb|left|alt=An illustrated map of Dublin with the route of the prologue time trial|The {{convert|5.6|km|abbr=on}} route of the [[Prologue (cycling)|prologue]] time trial around the streets of [[Dublin]], won by [[Chris Boardman]] ({{ct|C.A|1998a}})]]\nChris Boardman covered the {{convert|5.6|km|mi|abbr=on}} route of the prologue time trial fastest with a time of 6:12.36 minutes,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=31}} gaining his third Tour prologue victory.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=27}} The second, third and fourth-placed finishers Abraham Olano, Laurent Jalabert and Bobby Julich all had times that were four seconds more, with Jan Ullrich finishing sixth, five seconds behind Boardman.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=31}} Marco Pantani meanwhile had not bothered to preview the course and finished 181st out of the 189 starters, 48 seconds slower than the winning time.{{sfn|Rendell|2007|p=118}} Boardman was awarded the yellow and green jerseys as the leader of both the general and points classification respectively.<ref name=\"pcs-leaders\">{{cite web|title=Tour de France 1998 \u2013 Leaders overview|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/stages/leaders-overview|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=16 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216224428/https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/stages/leaders-overview|archive-date=16 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Tom Steels]] outsprinted [[Erik Zabel]] in stage 1's [[bunch sprint]] finish.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=35}} Steels came to the Tour with the full support of his {{ct|MAP|1998|nolink=yes}} squad for the sprints, unlike Zabel's {{ct|TEL|1998|nolink=yes}} who were focused on Ullrich's pursuit for overall victory.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=43}} [[Mario Cipollini]] ({{ct|SAE|1998|nolink=yes}}), a favourite for the stage win, was held up {{convert|8|km|abbr=on}} from the end when he was involved in a crash caused by his teammate.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Wicklow Welcomes Tour De France |series=Sunday Sport |date=12 July 1998 |url=https://www.rte.ie/archives/2018/0703/976039-tour-de-france-in-wicklow/ |accessdate=10 June 2019 |network=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |last=Willoughby |first=Roy (reporter) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529042355/https://www.rte.ie/archives/2018/0703/976039-tour-de-france-in-wicklow/ |archivedate=29 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=33}} Steels took the lead of the points classification from Boardman, who retained the overall lead.<ref name=\"pcs-leaders\" /> Steels's teammate [[Stefano Zanini]] was the first of a seven-rider [[Breakaway (cycling)|breakaway]] group to reach the summit of the [[Wicklow Gap]] mountain pass, claiming the Tour's first available mountains classification points and the first [[polka dot]] jersey.<ref name=\"pcs-leaders\" />{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=34\u201335}}\n\nUnlike other general classification favourites, who always rode at the front of the [[peloton]] (main group), Pantani spent the first days of the Tour at the back, surrounded by his teammates.{{sfn|Rendell|2007|p=118}}{{efn|Common cycling tactics dictate that riders should stay towards the front of the peloton to minimise the risk of being involved in a crash.{{sfn|Friebe|2014|p=148}}}} This almost cost him, when during stage 2, which was raced largely on the wide [[N25 road (Ireland)|N25]] road,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=39\u201340}} [[crosswind]]s split the field into several [[Echelon formation|echelons]]. Pantani was caught out and only came back when yellow jersey-wearer Boardman crashed heavily. In the aftermath, the peloton slowed down, allowing Pantani to catch back up.{{sfn|Friebe|2014|p=142}} Boardman meanwhile hit his head badly on a stone wall beside the road. He was taken to hospital and had to abandon the Tour.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pogatchnik |first=Shawn |title=Britain's Boardman out of Tour after crash |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/cycling/longterm/1998/tour/articles/boardman.htm |url-access=limited |accessdate=12 May 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=13 July 1998 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618162605/https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/cycling/longterm/1998/tour/articles/boardman.htm|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> {{ct|MAP|1998|nolink=yes}} rider [[J\u00e1n Svorada]] was involved in a crash with {{convert|15|km|abbr=on}} to go, but was able to recover and win the bunch sprint finish.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=42\u201343}} Zabel, who before the stage stood in eighth position overall,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=38}} had collected enough time bonuses in the [[intermediate sprint]]s to take the yellow jersey.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=40\u201341}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Move to France and evolving doping scandal===\n[[File:Richard VIRENQUE.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Portrait of Richard Virenque wearing a white, red and yellow cap|[[Richard Virenque]] (''pictured in 1993''), the leader of the {{ct|FES|1998}} team, which was expelled from the Tour after stage 6 following its management's admission to [[Doping in sport|doping]].]]\n{{ct|TEL|1998|nolink=yes}}'s [[Jens Heppner]] won stage 3 from a two-rider sprint with [[Xavier Jan]] of {{ct|FDJ|1998|nolink=yes}}, after the pair had broken away late from a nine-rider breakaway. [[Bo Hamburger]] of {{ct|ALM|1998|nolink=yes}}, who won two of the three intermediate sprints whilst in the escape group, took the overall lead.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=47\u201352}} Svorada took the lead of the points classification, with Festina's [[Pascal Herv\u00e9]] claiming the mountains classification lead.<ref name=\"pcs-leaders\" /> The second and third placers in the now much changed general classification also came from the breakaway, with [[George Hincapie]] ({{ct|DSC|1998|nolink=yes}}) two seconds down on Hamburger, and [[Stuart O'Grady]] ({{ct|C.A|1998a|nolink=yes}}) a further second behind.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=52\u201353}} Hincapie and O'Grady went head to head for the time bonuses in stage 4's three intermediate sprints, with O'Grady winning two of them to end the day with an eleven-second overall advantage over both Hincapie and Hamburger. The stage was won by [[Jeroen Blijlevens]] (TVM) from an uphill bunch sprint at [[Cholet]] in the [[Loire Valley]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=77}}{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=55\u201360}} Cipollini suffered his third crash of the Tour at the end of stage 4,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=58}} accumulating eight separate injuries,{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=81}} but was able to avoid the multiple crashes in the next stage to win the bunch sprint finish.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=79}} Svorada was disqualified for causing a crash at the end of the stage, losing the points he had earned from his tenth-place finish and ultimately the green jersey to Zabel,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=72}} who finished second in the stage.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=67}} Cipollini would again be successful on the following stage, winning the bunch sprint into [[Brive-la-Gaillarde]].{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=74}}\n\nAs the ferry reached French soil overnight into 14 July, the day of stage 3, all team vehicles were meticulously searched at customs.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=51}} During the day, Voet admitted to police that he had been following team orders, with Festina's team doctor [[Eric Rijkaert]] publicly denying he administered any banned substances. The next day, the team manager Bruno Roussel and Rijkaert were taken into police custody.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=19}} Before that start of stage 5,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=64}} Jean-Marie Leblanc announced at a press conference that the professional licences held by Roussel and Rijkaert had been provisionally suspended by the UCI, and at that same time, Festina riders Richard Virenque, Laurent Brochard and Laurent Dufaux stated their intention to carry on racing.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=19}} During stage 6, Roussel and Rijkaert confessed to systematic doping in the Festina squad. This led to the Tour organisation to expel the team ahead of the following stage.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2008|pp=246\u2013247}} Before the start of stage 7 Virenque, on behalf of Festina, held a private meeting with Leblanc to plead for the team to be allowed to continue, but to no avail.{{sfn|Fife|2000|p=202}}\n\nStage 7, the hilly and technical first long individual time trial, was won by Ullrich, 1:10 minutes ahead of {{ct|USP|1998|nolink=yes}}'s [[Tyler Hamilton]], with Julich in third a further eight seconds behind. O'Grady was fifteenth with a deficit of 3:17 minutes, and lost the yellow jersey to Ullrich, who was now 1:18 minutes in front of Hamburger and Julich on the same time in second and third respectively. Pantani finished thirty-third, 4:21 minutes slower than Ullrich, later saying that he had held himself back in anticipation of the upcoming Pyrenees.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=77\u201384}} Zanini regained the polka dot jersey.<ref name=\"pcs-leaders\" /> Stage 8 was hilly and had very high temperatures; it ended with a group of six riders which fought out the victory 7:45 minutes ahead of the peloton. The sprint was won by [[Jacky Durand]] of {{ct|ALM|1998|nolink=yes}}, who had been in an escape group on every road stage so far. Four riders from the group gained enough time to move to the top of the general classification, with {{ct|COF|1998|nolink=yes}}'s [[Laurent Desbiens]] taking the yellow jersey.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=85\u201391}} Temperatures increased to a high of {{convert|44|C}} during the following stage, which saw {{ct|RAB|1998|nolink=yes}} rider [[L\u00e9on van Bon]] win the final sprint which was contested between a four-man breakaway that was able to hold off the closing field by 12 seconds. Second place finisher [[Jens Voigt]] ({{ct|C.A|1998a|nolink=yes}}) collected enough mountains classification points from within the breakaway to take the polka dot jersey.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tour de France, Grand Tour \u2013 Stage 9 brief|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/tour98/stage9.html|access-date=13 June 2019|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|date=20 July 1998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701091323/http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/tour98/stage9.html|archive-date=1 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Two-time stage winner Cipollini dropped out during this stage.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=116}}{{efn|Over the course of his career, [[Mario Cipollini]] had shown a tendency to avoid riding high mountain stages, which did not suit him, instead focusing on the flat stages in the first week of the race. In fact, he never finished a Tour de France in seven appearances, neither the [[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]] in six attempts.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abt |first1=Samuel |title=Cycling: Hardly a sprint, but Cipollini heads toward the end |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/09/sports/IHT-cycling-hardly-a-sprint-but-cipollini-heads-toward-the-end.html |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=9 September 2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309122413/https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/09/sports/IHT-cycling-hardly-a-sprint-but-cipollini-heads-toward-the-end.html |archivedate=9 March 2020}}</ref>}}\n\n===Pyrenees===\n[[File:Corniche Aubisque Soulor.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A green mountainside with a low-gradient road|Stage 10's descent on the eastern side of the [[Col d'Aubisque]] mountain pass (''pictured'') saw a total of 30 riders fall in the wet and foggy conditions.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=100}}]]\nStage 10 saw the race move into the high mountains, starting with the Pyrenees. On the way to [[Luchon]], four mountain passes had to be crossed: the [[Col d'Aubisque]], the [[Col du Tourmalet]], the [[Col d'Aspin]] and lastly the [[Col de Peyresourde]], followed by {{convert|15.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} of downhill to the finish line.<ref name=\"letour-10\">{{cite web|title=Casino gamble pays great dividends|url=http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/10/|website=[[Tour de France]]|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=14 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041212232716/http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/10/|archivedate=12 December 2004}}</ref> A total of 30 riders fell on the wet and foggy descent of the Aubisque, including overall contenders Olano, Jalabert and Francesco Casagrande,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=99}} with the latter being one of six that retired from the race.<ref name=\"letour-10\" /> A three-rider breakaway of [[C\u00e9dric Vasseur]] ({{ct|C.A|1998a|nolink=yes}}) and {{ct|ALM|1998|nolink=yes}} teammates [[Rodolfo Massi]] and [[Alberto Elli]] had been formed by the foot of the Tourmalet. The pace set by {{ct|TEL|1998|nolink=yes}} halfway up this climb split the peloton, with yellow jersey wearer Desbiens dropped. Massi moved clear from his fellow breakers on the steep section midway on {{convert|13|km|mi|abbr=on}}-long last climb, and also at the same point after, a move by Ullrich formed a small group of elite riders which included pre-race favourites Pantani, Julich, Riis, Boogerd, Escart\u00edn and Jim\u00e9nez. Close to the top, Pantani launched a successful attack and summitted with an advantage of 42 seconds, but was unable to catch the soloing Massi on the descent,{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=99\u2013106}} who took the stage victory as well as the lead of the mountains classification.<ref name=\"letour-10\" /> Pantani finished second, 33 seconds behind. Ullrich followed with the other favourites, a further 23 seconds back, to regain the yellow jersey, while Julich moved up to second overall.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=105\u2013106}}\n\nThe following stage 11 featured the first mountain-top finish of the 1998 Tour. As they did in that stage, the peloton agreed not to begin racing until after the first {{convert|45|km|mi|abbr=on}}, when they stopped to pay their respects at the memorial to [[Fabio Casartelli]] on the [[Col de Portet d'Aspet]], who crashed and died there on the 1995 Tour.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nicholl|first=Robin|title=Ullrich produces a tour de force|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/ullrich-produces-a-tour-de-force-1250966.html|access-date=14 June 2019|work=[[The Independent]]|date=16 July 1997|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618162041/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/ullrich-produces-a-tour-de-force-1250966.html|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Longmore|first=Andrew|title=Tour de France: From quiet American to big noise|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tour-de-france-from-quiet-american-to-big-noise-1102779.html|access-date=14 June 2019|work=[[The Independent]]|date=27 June 1999|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618162144/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tour-de-france-from-quiet-american-to-big-noise-1102779.html|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> As the field headed the race at the bottom of the {{convert|16|km|mi|abbr=on}} climb to the finish at Plateau de Beille, Ullrich had a [[Flat tire|tyre puncture]]. Pantani was unaware of this and was about to attack, before being stopped by his teammate [[Roberto Conti]], as it breaches the [[Unspoken rule|unwritten rules]] of the peloton to attack a rider when they have mechanical issues. Having waited for Ullrich to regain contact, Pantani waited until {{convert|4|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the finish to attack, and after passing the sole breakaway rider, [[Roland Meier]] ({{ct|COF|1998|nolink=yes}}), he took the stage win.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=108\u2013112}}{{sfn|Friebe|2014|p=153}} Following Meier and a group of five led by Julich, Ullrich crossed the finish line in eighth place, 1:40 minutes down on Pantani. After the two stages in the Pyrenees, Ullrich led the general classification, 1:11 minutes ahead of Julich, with both Jalabert and Pantani 3:01 minutes down in third and fourth.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=112\u2013113}} Olano, a notable pre-race favourite, withdrew from the Tour halfway through the stage.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=108}}\n\n===Transition stages and rider unrest===\n[[File:Laurent JALABERT (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Portrait of wearing a pink jsery and headnad with \"ONCE\" insignia|[[Laurent Jalabert]] (''pictured in 1993'') of the {{ct|ONC|1998}} team was an influential figure in both of the Tour's rider [[Sit-in|sit-down]] protests during stages 12 and 17.]]\nAfter the rest day, stage 12 followed a flat course between [[Tarascon-sur-Ari\u00e8ge]] and [[Cap d'Agde]]. Anger had grown amongst the riders amid the treatment of them by the police and the press in light of the evolving Festina affair. They were also unhappy with the looming expulsion of the TVM team, against which the police had renewed their investigation which was started in March, as well as journalists going through waste containers at team hotels, searching for evidence of performance-enhancing drugs. Some riders also spoke out against the announcement by the UCI to move forward the introduction of new health tests.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=138}} As the riders lined up with their bikes at the start of the stage, Jalabert broadcast a statement on their behalf on the race's official station, Radio Tour, saying \"We are fed up with being treated like cattle. So we are going to behave like cattle.\"{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=118}}\n\nFollowing this, the majority of the riders sat down in the road and entered into a strike.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=118}} The biggest influence during the strike was attributed to Jalabert, Blijlevens, [[Max Sciandri]] ({{ct|FDJ|1998|nolink=yes}}), and [[Prudencio Indur\u00e1in]] ({{ct|VIT|1998|nolink=yes}}) as well as ONCE's team manager [[Manolo Saiz]].{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pages=139\u2013140}} Leblanc negotiated with all of the team managers and they voted 14\u20136 in agreement to begin the stage. The peloton and vehicles slowly set off, but a Jalabert-led group of about 40 refused. They eventually relented and caught up to the rest {{convert|16|km|mi|abbr=on}} ahead, and the race started, exactly two hours after the scheduled time. Jalabert then went on the attack over a short climb with his brother [[Nicolas Jalabert|Nicolas]] ({{ct|COF|1998|nolink=yes}}) and [[Bart Voskamp]] (TVM), who built up a lead of over five minutes. Team Telekom gave chase at a high pace, temporarily putting Pantani into difficulty as crosswinds created echelons in the peloton.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pages=141\u2013143}}{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=119\u2013121}} The trio of escapees were eventually brought back. Steels took his second stage win of the Tour in a bunch sprint finish.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=119\u2013122}} The shortened stage was run at an average speed of {{convert|48.764|kph|mph|abbr=on}}, breaking the Tour record of the fastest ever stage over {{convert|200|km|mi|abbr=on}},{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=122}} as well as the third-fastest of any distance stage in Tour history.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=143}}\n\nStage 13 saw a breakaway by six riders, among them [[Daniele Nardello]] and [[Andrea Tafi (cyclist)|Andrea Tafi]], both of Team {{ct|MAP|1998|nolink=yes}}. They worked together at the finish to ensure Nardello took Mapei's fourth stage win. At the only classified climb of the day, [[Luc Leblanc]] ({{ct|POL|1998|nolink=yes}}) put in an attack, but was brought back by Riis.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=152}} The following day's stage brought the Tour to [[Grenoble]] at the foot of the Alps. The stage was won by O'Grady, again from a breakaway.<ref name=\"cn-14\">{{cite news|title=Tour de France, Grand Tour \u2013 Stage 14 brief|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/tour98/stage14.html|access-date=17 June 2019|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|date=26 July 1998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322165454/http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/tour98/stage14.html|archive-date=22 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In the press conference after, Ullrich was asked whether his team would be capable of supporting him in the Alps and, after initially appearing upbeat, he ended his response with: \"Even if I don't have the yellow jersey in Paris, I want to give my compliments to the team\".{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=134\u2013135}} Pantani, who still stood at fourth overall, was quoted saying: \"My main goal now is to win in Les Deux-Alpes.\"<ref name=\"cn-14\" />\n\n===Alps and second strike===\n[[File:Pantani Bike 1998 TdF.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A turquoise and yellow Bianchi bicycle hung up at a cycle show stand|One of the [[racing bicycle]]s that was used by [[Marco Pantani]] during the Tour's mountain stages]]\nStage 15 was the first of three Alpine stages. After a warm start in Grenoble, the weather soon deteriorated, with cold temperatures, rain and fog impeding the riders. The route contained four classified climbs, including the ''hors categorie'' [[Col de la Croix de Fer]] and Col du Galibier, and ending with a summit finish at Les Deux Alpes.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=164}} On the Croix de Fer, Massi bridged over to a breakaway group and scored maximum points for the mountains classification, a feat he repeated on the second climb of the day, the [[Col du T\u00e9l\u00e9graphe]]. By this point, the lead group contained only Massi, [[Christophe Rinero]] ({{ct|COF|1998|nolink=yes}}) and [[Marcos-Antonio Serrano]] ({{ct|KEL|1998|nolink=yes}}). Behind them in the group of the main favourites, the high climbing tempo put Jalabert into difficulty, which ultimately saw him drop far down the general classification by the end of the stage.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=165}} After the short descent of the T\u00e9l\u00e9graphe, the race reached the Galibier, where Riis cracked following his work reeling back attackers, leaving Ullrich without a teammate.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=166}} With {{convert|6|km|mi|abbr=on}} remaining to the summit of the Galibier, Pantani made the decisive move of the race, attacking from the group of favourites.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=141}} By the summit of the climb, Pantani had passed all the breakaway riders and was out in front alone, leading by ten seconds. Ullrich reached the top 2:41 minutes behind Pantani. Crucially, unlike Pantani, he did not wear a raincoat during the descent. He subsequently suffered from the cold and [[hyperglycemia]] for the rest of the stage.{{sfn|Rendell|2007|pages=124\u2013126}} The breakaway caught up to Pantani on the descent of the Galibier, forming a group of strong climbers. Before the final climb to Les Deux Alpes, Ullrich had a tyre puncture and was distanced by the group of chasers. On the climb, Pantani soon moved clear of his group and took the stage victory, almost two minutes ahead of Massi in second place. Ullrich finished with teammates [[Udo B\u00f6lts]] and Riis 8:57 minutes after Pantani, who took over the yellow jersey. He led Julich by 3:53 minutes, with Escart\u00edn in third place in the general classification, ahead of Ullrich.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=142\u2013146}}\n\nBefore the following stage to [[Albertville]], speculation spread that Ullrich would abandon the race.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=187}} Pantani's Mercatone Uno team coped well in defending his yellow over the four lesser categorised climbs, until the race reached the ''hors categorie'' final climb, the [[Col de la Madeleine]], when Ullrich attacked, with only Pantani able to follow. Ullrich led the duo up the rest of the climb as they passed the breakaway riders and increased their advantage over the chasing Julich, who was accompanied by two teammates. The pair held their lead of around two minutes along the final {{convert|17|km|mi|abbr=on}} of flat, where at the finish, Ullrich outsprinted Pantani to the stage win. Pantani now led Julich by 5:42 minutes, with Ullrich third, just over six minutes behind.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=147\u2013152}}\n\nAnother police raid on the TVM team and news about alleged mistreatment of the Festina riders while in custody led to another riders' strike on stage 17. After a brief stop of two minutes at the start, the riders rode slowly to the first intermediate sprint of the day, where they climbed off their bikes and sat on the road. Jalabert climbed into his team car and retired from the race. Meanwhile, Jean-Marie Leblanc negotiated with the riders and collected guarantees from a civil servant from the [[Ministry of the Interior (France)|French Ministry of the Interior]], who was visiting the Tour as a guest, that police treatment of the riders would improve. Nevertheless, the entire ONCE team followed their leader Jalabert and abandoned. As the riders slowly got moving again, they ripped off their race numbers as a further sign of protest. Luc Leblanc retired later in the stage. At the feed zone, the Banesto squad joined their fellow Spanish-based ONCE team in quitting, as well as the Italian-based Riso Scotti team. The field reached the finishing town, [[Aix-les-Bains]], two hours behind schedule. The TVM team was allowed to cross the line first as a sign of solidarity; while the stage was annulled and no results counted. Overnight, two more Spanish-based teams, Kelme and Vitalicio Seguros, also decided not to carry on in the Tour. This caused the retirement of the fourth rider overall, Escart\u00edn of Kelme.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pages=202\u2013223}}\n\n===Conclusion===\n[[File:Marco Pantani.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Portrait of Marco Pantani wearing a bandana and glasses on his head|[[Marco Pantani]] (''pictured in 1997'') was the overall winner of the Tour, completing the [[Giro-Tour double]], as he had also won the [[1998 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]] earlier in the season.]]\nBefore stage 18 into [[Neuch\u00e2tel]] in Switzerland, police held Massi, who was still the leader in the mountains classification, for questioning after [[corticoid]]s were allegedly found in his room during a search of the Casino team hotel.{{efn|Massi was later cleared of all charges.<ref>{{cite news |title='Festina Affair': A timeline |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/988530.stm |accessdate=30 October 2019 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=24 October 2000}}</ref>}} He was therefore unable to start the stage,<ref name=\"wp-troubled\">{{cite news |last1=Thomazeau |first1=Francois |title=Troubled Tour Resumes; Steels Wins 18th Stage |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/cycling/longterm/1998/tour/articles/tour31.htm |url-access=limited |accessdate=4 June 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=30 July 1998|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604145145/https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/cycling/longterm/1998/tour/articles/tour31.htm|archive-date=4 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the lead of the mountains classification was passed to the second placed rider, Rinero.<ref name=\"pcs-leaders\" /> Victory went to Steels, who outsprinted Zabel and O'Grady at the finish.<ref name=\"wp-troubled\"  /> The remaining five riders from TVM exited the race on Swiss soil before the start of the following day. Stage 19 went back into France and saw a breakaway of 13 riders. Four riders broke away from the lead group to contest the stage win between them, with [[Magnus B\u00e4ckstedt]] ({{ct|C.A|1998a|nolink=yes}}) coming out on top.<ref>{{cite news |last=Abt |first=Samuel |author-link=Samuel Abt |title=Backstedt's Late Surge Gives Him Slim Victory |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/08/01/sports/cycling-tour-de-france-backstedt-s-late-surge-gives-him-slim-victory.html |accessdate=4 June 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=1 August 1998 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527073216/http://www.nytimes.com/1998/08/01/sports/cycling-tour-de-france-backstedt-s-late-surge-gives-him-slim-victory.html |archive-date=27 May 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe penultimate stage saw the last individual time trial of the race to [[Le Creusot]]. Ullrich won the stage, 1:01 minutes ahead of Julich, to move into second place overall. Pantani finished the stage third, 2:35 minutes behind Ullrich, effectively sealing his victory in the general classification.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|pp=174\u2013175}} The final stage on the Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es in Paris was won by Steels from a bunch sprint, while Pantani finished safely in the peloton to secure the Tour win.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=177}} Ullrich ended the Tour in second place, with a deficit of 3:21 minutes, with Julich a further 47 seconds behind in third.<ref name=\"letour-21-gc\">{{cite web|title=Stage 21: Melun \u2013 Paris-Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es (147,5 km): Overall standings|url=http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/itg.html|website=[[Tour de France]]|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=23 March 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991221194735/http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/itg.html|archivedate=21 December 1999}}</ref> Pantani was greeted on the podium by [[Felice Gimondi]], who had been invited by Jean-Marie Leblanc to present to the crowd the first Italian winner since his own victory in [[1965 Tour de France|1965]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Westemeyer |first1=Susan |title=Gimondi on Pantani film and cyclist |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/gimondi-on-pantani-film-and-cyclist/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=19 August 2019 |date=5 February 2007}}</ref> Zabel won his third consecutive points classification with a total of 327, 97 ahead of O'Grady in second.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=119}}<ref name=\"letour-21-points\">{{cite web|title=Stage 21: Melun \u2013 Paris-Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es (147,5 km): Overall sprinters|url=http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/ipg.html|website=[[Tour de France]]|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=23 March 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991221164955/http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/ipg.html|archivedate=21 December 1999}}</ref> Although Pantani won two high mountain stages, the mountains classification was won by a more consistent Rinero, whose total of 200 points was 25 more than that of second-placed Pantani.<ref name=\"letour-21-mountains\">{{cite web|title=Stage 21: Melun \u2013 Paris-Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es (147,5 km): Overall climbers|url=http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/img.html|website=[[Tour de France]]|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=23 March 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991221125924/http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/img.html|archivedate=21 December 1999}}</ref> Due to the high number of abandons because of the Festina affair, only 96 riders reached the finish in Paris.<ref name=\"letour-21-gc\" /> Only Team Telekom and U.S. Postal Service ended the Tour with all nine riders still racing.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|p=39}}\n\n===Doping===\n{{main|Doping at the 1998 Tour de France}}\nThe prevalence of EPO in the cycling peloton had been a topic of debate since the early 1990s.{{sfn|Woodland|2003|p=142}} First news stories about the drug appeared in 1994.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=106}} The UCI gave the task of developing a test for EPO to [[Francesco Conconi]], a professor at the [[University of Ferrara]], Italy, and a member of the UCI Medical Commission. In June 1996, Conconi, seemingly unable to find a definite test for the substance,{{efn|Around the year 2000, investigations in Italy revealed that Conconi had used the money given to him by the UCI to provide EPO to professional cyclists.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=109}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Capodacqua |first1=Eugenio |title=Ecco il doping di Conconi |trans-title=Here is the doping of Conconi|url=https://www.repubblica.it/online/sport/pantapro/capo/capo.html |accessdate=30 October 2019 |work=[[la Repubblica]] |date=27 October 2000 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030105104/https://www.repubblica.it/online/sport/pantapro/capo/capo.html |archivedate=30 October 2019 |language=Italian}}</ref> A promising test for EPO by Canadian scientist Guy Brisson, who conducted a trial run during the [[1996 Tour de Suisse]] and found indications of EPO abuse in all tested 77 riders, was not followed up by the UCI, due to fear that the test would not \"stand up to legal challenges\".{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pp=112\u2013113}}}} proposed to the UCI to introduce a test for an athlete's [[hematocrit]] level instead, meaning to test the amount of [[Red blood cell|red cells]] in the blood.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=109}} During the UCI's meeting in [[Geneva]], Switzerland, on 24 January 1997, the procedure, labelled as a \"health test\", limiting the allowed hematocrit level to 50 per cent, was introduced.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Daniel T. |last2=Ashenden |first2=Michael |last3=Parisotto |first3=Robin |last4=Pyne |first4=David |last5=Hahn |first5=Allan G. |title=Blood Testing for Professional Cyclists: What's a fair hematocrit limit? |url=http://www.sportsci.org/news/news9703/AISblood.html |website=sportsci.org |publisher=Sportscience News |accessdate=16 August 2019 |date=1997}}</ref> Failing to test below the given value resulted in the rider being barred from competing for a two-week period. However, as cycling journalist [[Alasdair Fotheringham]] described it, \"the 50 per cent threshold became a target to aim for\" instead of a reliable deterrent to using EPO.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=107}}\n\nThe doping scandal that occurred throughout the Tour became known as the [[Festina affair]],<ref name=\"cn_1998\">{{cite web |last1=Whittle |first1=Jeremy |title=The 1998 Tour de France: Police raids, arrests, protests... and a bike race |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/features/the-1998-tour-de-france-police-raids-arrests-protests-and-a-bike-race/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=25 June 2019 |date=3 March 2017}}</ref> starting with the arrest of Voet.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tour rocked by drugs arrest |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/special_report/1998/07/98/tour_de_france/130515.stm |accessdate=25 June 2019 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=11 July 1998}}</ref> Initially the doping suspicion only surrounded the Festina and TVM teams, but later investigations and retrospective tests revealed the doping abuse was far more widespread. Therefore, this edition of the Tour also became nicknamed by many media sources as the \"Tour de Farce\"{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=Dust jacket}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Fotheringham|first=William|author-link=William Fotheringham|title=Scandal revives doping fears|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2004/jan/28/cycling.cycling|access-date=18 June 2019|work=[[TheGuardian.com]]|date=28 January 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618164423/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2004/jan/28/cycling.cycling|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ausblenden und Gesundbeten |trans-title=Suppressing and Healing Through Faith |url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-7941085.html |accessdate=4 June 2019 |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |issue=31/1998 |page=104 |language=German |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110222014555/http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-7941085.html |archive-date=22 February 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> or \"Tour du Dopage\" (Tour of Doping).<ref>{{cite news |title=De positieve renners van de Tour du dopage |trans-title=The positive riders of the Tour du Dopage |url=https://www.volkskrant.nl/nieuws-achtergrond/de-positieve-renners-van-de-tour-du-dopage~q0570442/ |accessdate=25 June 2019 |work=[[de Volkskrant]] |date=24 July 2013 |language=Dutch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Radsport: TVM-Aff\u00e4re 1998: Blijlevens und Voskamp gestehen Epo-Doping | trans-title=TVM affair: Blijlevens and Voskamp admit to EPO doping| url=https://www.focus.de/sport/radsport/radsport-tvm-affaere-1998-blijlevens-und-voskamp-gestehen-epo-doping_id_3983157.html |accessdate=25 June 2019 |work=[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]] |agency=[[Sport-Informations-Dienst]] |date=11 July 2014 |language=German}}</ref>{{sfn|Waddington|2001|p=159}} Following Festina's expulsion from the race, the police's investigation against the TVM team was made public by ''[[Le Parisien]]'' and the case reopened.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=96}}\n\nThe riders in the Tour reacted differently to the developing scandal. [[Rolf Aldag]] ({{ct|TEL|1998|nolink=yes}}) says he flushed his doping products down the toilet before the race began in Dublin.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=1}} His teammate Bjarne Riis stated in his autobiography that he disposed of his vials of EPO in the toilet after stage 3.{{sfn|Riis|Pedersen|2012|p=171}} Likewise, the U.S. Postal team flushed their drugs down the toilet following Voet's arrest, according to Tyler Hamilton.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=92}} According to J\u00f6rg Jaksche, the Polti squad hid their supply of EPO in a vacuum cleaner on the team bus, while he also stated his belief that most Italian teams kept their drugs during the race as well. [[Philippe Gaumont]] claimed in his autobiography that the Cofidis team were told by the team management to destroy their substances on the day that the Festina team was expelled, with the riders subsequently going into a forest and disposing of the products.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pp=60\u201361}} Julich meanwhile states that he quit doping altogether during the 1998 Tour.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=279}}\n\nAfter their arrests, Voet, Roussel, and Rijckaert gave confessions of the doping practices at Festina to the police. Roussel stated that one per cent of the team's budget (around \u20ac40,000) was used to pay for EPO and [[human growth hormone]]s.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=71}} The riders on Festina were placed under custody and brought into individual prison cells, and allegedly subjected to [[Body cavity search|cavity search]]es. On 24 July, four Festina riders had confessed to taking performance-enhancing drugs, with the first being Alex Z\u00fclle. The only riders to deny the allegations were Virenque and [[Neil Stephens]].{{efn|Stephens maintains that he took EPO unknowingly, having thought it to be vitamin supplements.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aubrey |first1=Jane |title=Orica-GreenEdge owner unaware of Stephens' past admissions |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/orica-greenedge-owner-unaware-of-stephens-past-admissions/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=16 August 2019 |date=12 December 2012}}</ref>}}{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pp=135\u2013138}} Examinations carried out on the nine Festina riders on 23 July, with the results being published on 28 November, revealing that eight riders took EPO and four amphetamines. Virenque was the only rider not to test positive in these tests.<ref name=\"cn_history\">{{cite web |title=News for October 25, 2000 |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/2000/oct00/oct25news.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=2 September 2019 |date=25 October 2000}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 July, the Tour's rest day, TVM's manager Cees Priem and team doctor Andrei Mikhailov were also arrested by the police.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=135}} At the beginning of August, team ''soigneur'' Johannes Moors was taken into custody as well.<ref name=\"cn_4august98\">{{cite web |title=News for August 4, 1998: The drugs scandal update |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/aug98/aug4.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=4 August 1998}}</ref> Priem and Moors were released on 10 August.<ref name=cn_11august>{{cite web |title=News for August 11, 1998: Drugs Scandal update |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/aug98/aug11.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=11 August 1998}}</ref>  The TVM riders were also questioned by the police on 4 August and held for about 12 hours, before they were released.<ref>{{cite web |title=Second Edition News for August 4, 1998: The drugs scandal update |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/aug98/aug4a.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=4 August 1998}}</ref> However, no banned substances were found during the raid at TVM's team hotel during the Tour.<ref>{{cite web |title=News for August 8, 1998: The drugs scandal update |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/aug98/aug8.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=8 August 1998}}</ref> At ONCE and BigMat, police did find performance-enhancing drugs during their raids. ONCE maintained that the substances were for medical use of the team staff.<ref>{{cite web |title=News for August 4, 1998: The drugs scandal update |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/aug98/aug4.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=4 August 1998}}</ref> Police called in twelve riders from BigMat for questioning along with the ''[[directeur sportif]]'' and some ''soigneurs'' a week after the end of the Tour because of \"330 bottles and ampoules of drugs\" found in the team's truck.<ref>{{cite web |title=News for August 15, 1998: Drugs Update |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/aug98/aug15.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=15 August 1998}}</ref>\n\nThe legal investigation about doping at the 1998 Tour was given to judge Patrick Keil shortly after the race concluded. He handed in his 5539-page report on the matter at the beginning of July 1999, which laid the groundwork for subsequent legal proceedings against team staff and riders.<ref>{{cite web |title=News for July 2, 1999 |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1999/jul99/jul2.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=2 September 2019 |date=2 July 1999}}</ref> Virenque confessed during a court hearing concerning the Festina affair, on 24 October 2000.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hamoir |first1=Oliver |title=Virenque: 'I took drugs, I had no choice' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/virenque-i-took-drugs-i-had-no-choice-637089.html |accessdate=16 August 2019 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=25 October 2000}}</ref> Virenque received a nine-month racing ban and a suspended prison sentence.{{efn|Virenque appealed the decision at the [[Court of Arbitration for Sport]] in [[Lausanne]], Switzerland. The Court considered to turn his ban into a suspended sentence. They eventually upheld the verdict, but brought its start date forward, meaning Virenque was able to return to competition on 14 August 2001.<ref>{{cite web |title=News for March 13, 2001: Virenque's suspension brought forward |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/2001/mar01/mar13news.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=13 March 2001}}</ref>}} Voet was sentenced to a suspended ten months in prison and a fine of 3,000 franc. Roussell received a one-year suspended sentence and a 50,000 franc fine. Lesser verdicts were handed out to \"two masseurs, the team's logistics manager, the team doctor at the Spanish ONCE team, Nicolas Terrados, and two pharmacists\".<ref name=\"guardian_verdict\">{{cite news |last1=Fotheringham |first1=William |author-link=William Fotheringham |title=Festina trial ends with fines and a warning |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/story/0,3604,415051,00.html |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=23 December 2000}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Tour, 108 tests for performance-enhancing drugs were carried out by France's main anti-doping laboratory in [[Ch\u00e2tenay-Malabry]]. All of them were negative.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=101}}{{sfn|Waddington|Smith|2009|p=148}} In 2004, 60 remaining anti-doping samples given by riders during the 1998 Tour were tested retrospectively for recombinant EPO by using three recently developed detection methods. The results of these tests were published to have returned 44 positives and 9 negatives, with the remaining 7 samples not returning any result due to sample degradation. At first, the rider names with a positive sample were not made public, as it had only been conducted as scientific research.<ref name=\"Derni\u00e8re Heure\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dhnet.be/sports/tourdefrance/1998-plane-sur-le-centieme-tour-de-france-51cbd867357030bb907bbd54|title=1998 plane sur le centi\u00e8me Tour de France|trans-title=1998 flat on the hundredth Tour de France|language=French|work=[[La Derni\u00e8re Heure]]|date=27 June 2013|accessdate=28 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130630073932/http://www.dhnet.be/sports/tourdefrance/1998-plane-sur-le-centieme-tour-de-france-51cbd867357030bb907bbd54|archive-date=30 June 2013|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, the anti-doping committee of the [[French Senate]] decided it would benefit the current doping fight to shed full light on the past, and so decided&nbsp;\u2013 as part of their \"Commission of Inquiry into the effectiveness of the fight against doping\" report&nbsp;\u2013 to publish all sample IDs along with the result of the retrospective test. This publication revealed, that the 9 negative samples belonged to 5 riders (of whom two nevertheless had confessed using EPO in that Tour), while the 44 positive samples belonged to 33 riders&nbsp;\u2013 including race winner Pantani, Ullrich, Julich, and Zabel.<ref name=\"Positive EPO cases\">{{cite web|title=Cipollini, Livingston among 1998 Tour riders positive for EPO|url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2013/07/news/pantini-ullrich-among-1998-tour-riders-positive-for-epo_296750|work=[[VeloNews]]|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=28 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728091214/http://velonews.competitor.com/2013/07/news/pantini-ullrich-among-1998-tour-riders-positive-for-epo_296750|archive-date=28 July 2013|url-status=live|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"44 Positive EPO Samples\">{{cite web|title=Rapport Fait au nom de la commission d\u2019enqu\u00eate sur l\u2019efficacit\u00e9 de la lutte contre le dopage (Annexe 6: R\u00e9sultats test EPO Tour De France 1998 et 1999)|trans-title=Report Made on behalf of the commission of inquiry into the effectiveness of the fight against doping (Appendix 6: EPO test results Tour de France 1998 and 1999)|url=http://www.senat.fr/rap/r12-782-2/r12-782-21.pdf|format=PDF|language=French|work=N\u00b0 782, S\u00e9nat Session Extraordinaire de 2012\u20132013|publisher=French Senate|date=17 July 2013|accessdate=28 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130806234902/http://www.senat.fr/rap/r12-782-2/r12-782-21.pdf|archive-date=6 August 2013|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> Julich had already admitted using EPO from August 1996 to July 1998 one year prior to this publication.<ref name=\"Julich confession\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/exclusive-bobby-julich-doping-confession|title=Exclusive: Bobby Julich doping confession|website=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|date=25 October 2012|accessdate=25 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025181017/http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/exclusive-bobby-julich-doping-confession|archive-date=25 October 2012|url-status=live|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Classification leadership and minor prizes==\n[[File:Erik ZABEL (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Portrait of Erik Zabel wearing a pink jersey and cap|[[Erik Zabel]] ({{ct|TEL|1998}}, ''pictured in 2002'') won the [[points classification in the Tour de France|points classification]] for the third time in a row.]]\nThere were several classifications in the 1998 Tour de France.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=452\u2013455}} The most important was the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]], calculated by adding each cyclist's finishing times on each stage. The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey; the winner of this classification is considered the winner of the Tour.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=452\u2013453}} Jan Ullrich wore the yellow jersey in the prologue as the winner of the previous edition.{{sfn|Edwards et al.|1998|p=27}} Time bonuses were given during the first half of the Tour to the first three finishers on each stage, excluding mountain stages and time trials. The winner received a 20-second bonus, the second finisher 12 seconds and the third rider 8 seconds.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|pages=128\u2013129}} During the first half of the race, intermediate sprints also had time bonuses, with bonuses of 6, 4, and 2 seconds given to the first three riders to cross the line.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|p=183}}\n\nAdditionally, there was a [[points classification in the Tour de France|points classification]], in which cyclists got points for finishing among the best in a stage finish, or in intermediate sprints.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=453\u2013454}} In flat stages, the first 25 finishers received points, 35 for the stage winner down to 1 point for 25th place. In medium mountain stages, the top-20 finishers received points, with 25 points for the stage winner down to 1 point. In mountain stages, the first 15 finishers received points, with 20 points given to the stage winner. In time trials, 15 points were given to the winner, down to 1 point for the tenth-placed finisher.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|p=154}} Points could also be won during intermediate sprints along the race route, with 6, 4, and 2 points for the first three riders across the line respectively.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|p=182}} The cyclist with the most points led the classification, and was identified by a green jersey.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=453\u2013454}}\n\nThere was also a [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]]. Most stages of the race included one or more categorised climbs, in which points were awarded to the riders that reached the summit first. The climbs were categorised as fourth-, third-, second- or first-category and ''hors cat\u00e9gorie'', with the more difficult climbs rated lower.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}} The first rider to cross the summit of an ''hors cat\u00e9gorie'' climb was given 40 points (down to 1 point for the 15th rider). Twelve riders received points for first category climbs, with 30 for the first rider to reach the summit. Second-, third- and fourth-category climbs gave 20, 10 and 5 points to the first rider respectively.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|p=164}} The cyclist with the most points led the classification, wearing a white jersey with red polka dots.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=454}}\n\nThe [[Young rider classification in the Tour de France|young rider classification]], which was not marked by a jersey, was decided the same way as the general classification, but only riders under 26 years were eligible.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=454\u2013455}} This meant that in order to compete in the classification, a rider had to be born after 1 January 1973. 34 out of the 189 starters were eligible.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|pages=174\u2013175}} Jan Ullrich won the classification for the third time in a row.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|p=176}}\n\nFor the [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team classification]], the times of the best three cyclists per team on each stage were added; the leading team was the team with the lowest total time.{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=455}}\n\nIn addition, there was a [[Combativity award in the Tour de France|combativity award]] given after each mass-start stage to the cyclist considered the most combative. The winner of the award wore a red number bib during the next stage, this feature was introduced for the first time in 1998. The decision was made by a jury composed of journalists who gave points. The cyclist with the most points from votes in all stages led the combativity classification.{{sfn|van den Akker|2018|pp=211\u2013216}}{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|p=455}} Jacky Durand won this classification, and was given overall the super-combativity award.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=89}} The [[Souvenir Henri Desgrange]] was given in honour of Tour founder [[Henri Desgrange]] to the first rider to pass the summit of the Col du Galibier on stage 15. The winner of the prize was Marco Pantani.<ref name=\"cn-15\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:smaller; clear:both;\"\n|+Classification leadership by stage<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour de France 1998 \u2013 Leaders overview|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/stages/leaders-overview|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=16 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216224428/https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/tour-de-france/1998/gc/stages/leaders-overview|archive-date=16 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"tdf-statistics\">{{cite web|last=van den Akker|first=Pieter|title=Informatie over de Tour de France van 1998|trans-title=Information about the Tour de France from 1998|url=http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1998|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302052644/http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1998|archivedate=2 March 2019|language=Dutch|website=TourDeFranceStatistieken.nl|accessdate=2 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey yellow.svg|25px|link=General classification in the Tour de France|alt=A yellow jersey.]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Points classification in the Tour de France|Points classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey green.svg|25px|link=Points classification in the Tour de France|alt=A green jersey]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Mountains classification in the Tour de France|Mountains classification]]<br />[[File:Jersey polkadot.svg|25px|link=Mountains classification in the Tour de France|alt=A white jersey with red polka dots.]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Young rider classification in the Tour de France|Young rider classification]]{{efn|A white jersey was not awarded to the leader of the young rider classification between [[1989 Tour de France|1989]] and [[1999 Tour de France|1999]].{{sfn|Nauright|Parrish|2012|pp=454\u2013455}}}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Team classification in the Tour de France|Team classification]]<!-- no yellow number bib given before 2006 -->\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:22%;\" colspan=\"2\" | [[Combativity award in the Tour de France|Combativity]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" | [[File:Jersey red number.svg|20px|link=Combativity award in the Tour de France|alt=A white jersey with a red number bib.]] Award\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12%;\" | Classification\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Prologue|P]]\n| [[Chris Boardman]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Chris Boardman]]\n| style=\"background:#9CE97B;\" | [[Chris Boardman]]\n| ''no award''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Jan Ullrich]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{ct|FES|1998}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''no award''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 1|1]]\n| [[Tom Steels]]\n| style=\"background:#9CE97B;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Tom Steels]]\n| style=\"background:#FFA8A4;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Stefano Zanini]]\n| style=\"background:#E4B3AB;\" | [[Jacky Durand]]\n| rowspan=\"21\" | [[Jacky Durand]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 2|2]]\n| [[J\u00e1n Svorada]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" | [[Erik Zabel]]\n| style=\"background:#E4B3AB;\" | [[Christophe Agnolutto]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1998 Tour de France, Prologue to Stage 11#Stage 3|3]]\n| [[Jens Heppner]]\n| style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" | [[Bo Hamburger]]\n| style=\"background:#9CE97B;\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[J\u00e1n Svorada]]\n| style=\"background:#FFA8A4;\" rowspan=\"4\" | [[Pascal Herv\u00e9]]\n| [[George Hincapie]]\n| row