}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| {{ct|COF|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 278h 29' 58\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| {{ct|ALM|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 29' 09\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| {{ct|USP|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 41' 40\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| {{ct|TEL|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 46' 01\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| {{ct|LOT|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 04' 14\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| {{ct|POL|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 06' 32\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| {{ct|RAB|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 46' 20\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| {{ct|MAP|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 59' 53\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| {{ct|AUB|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 03' 32\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| {{ct|UNO|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 23' 04\"\n|}\n\n{{columns-end}}\n\n===Combativity classification===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Final combativity classification (1\u201310)<ref>{{cite web|title=Stage 21: Melun \u2013 Paris-Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es (147,5 km): Overall combativity|url=http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/icg.html|website=[[Tour de France]]|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=10 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991225112611/http://www.letour.com/98us/etapes/21/classements/icg.html|archivedate=25 December 1999}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n|{{flagathlete|[[Jacky Durand]]|FRA}} [[File:Jersey red number.svg|20px|link=Combativity award in the Tour de France|alt=A white jersey with a red number bib.]] || {{ct|ALM|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 94\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n|{{flagathlete|[[Andrea Tafi (cyclist)|Andrea Tafi]]|ITA}} || {{ct|MAP|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 51\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n|{{flagathlete|[[St\u00e9phane Heulot]]|FRA}} || {{ct|FDJ|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 49\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n|{{flagathlete|[[C\u00e9dric Vasseur]]|FRA}} || {{ct|C.A|1998a}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 47\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n|{{flagathlete|[[Christophe Agnolutto]]|FRA}} || {{ct|ALM|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 43\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n|{{flagathlete|[[Laurent Desbiens]]|FRA}} || {{ct|COF|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 35\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n|{{flagathlete|[[Fabio Roscioli]]|ITA}} || {{ct|ASI|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 33\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n|{{flagathlete|[[Thierry Gouvenou]]|FRA}} || {{ct|AUB|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 30\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n|{{flagathlete|[[Christophe Rinero]]|FRA}} [[File:Jersey polkadot.svg|20px|link=Mountains classification in the Tour de France|alt=A white jersey with red polka dots.]] || {{ct|COF|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 28\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n|{{flagathlete|[[Pascal Chanteur]]|FRA}} || {{ct|CSO|1998}} || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 28\n|}\n\n==UCI Road Rankings==\n\nRiders in the Tour competed individually, as well as for their teams and nations, for points that contributed towards the UCI Road Rankings, which included all [[UCI race classifications|UCI races]].{{sfn|''UCI Rules''|1998|pp=107\u2013108}} Points were awarded to all riders in the general classification, to the top ten finishers in each stage, and each yellow jersey given at the end of a stage.{{sfn|''UCI Rules''|1998|pp=108\u2013109}} The points accrued by Marco Pantani moved him from fifth position to fourth in the individual ranking, with Laurent Jalabert, who did not finish the Tour, holding his lead. {{ct|FES|1998|nolink=yes}} retained their lead of the team ranking, ahead of second-placed {{ct|MAP|1998|nolink=yes}}. Italy remained as leaders of the nations ranking, with Switzerland second.<ref name=\"uci-rankings-02-08-98\">{{cite web|title=UCI Road Rankings \u2013 2 August 1998|url=http://www.uci.ch/english/road/data/men_980802.pdf|accessdate=24 March 2019|publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|date=3 August 1998|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000830115625/http://www.uci.ch/english/road/data/men_980802.pdf|archivedate=30 August 2000}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+UCI Individual Classification ranking on 2 August 1998 (1\u201310)<ref name=\"uci-rankings-02-08-98\" />\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank\n! scope=\"col\" | {{abbr|Prev.|Previous rank}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Name\n! scope=\"col\" | Team\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Laurent Jalabert]]|FRA}}\n| {{ct|ONC|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 2961.00\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alex Z\u00fclle]]|SUI}}\n| {{ct|FES|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 2196.00\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Michele Bartoli]]|ITA}}\n| {{ct|ASI|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 2097.00\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Marco Pantani]]|ITA}}\n| {{ct|UNO|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1961.00\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Laurent Dufaux]]|SUI}}\n| {{ct|FES|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1535.80\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Andrei Tchmil]]|BEL}}\n| {{ct|LOT|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1400.00\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Davide Rebellin]]|ITA}}\n| {{ct|PLT|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1301.00\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8\n| {{flagathlete|[[Francesco Casagrande]]|ITA}}\n| {{ct|COF|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1290.00\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 12\n| {{flagathlete|[[Andrea Tafi (cyclist)|Andrea Tafi]]|ITA}}\n| {{ct|MAP|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1281.50\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16\n| {{flagathlete|[[Michael Boogerd]]|NED}}\n| {{ct|RAB|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1279.00\n|}\n\n==Aftermath==\n{{quote box|quote=If we hadn't had those scandals, the Festina affair and so on, we would have continued in the world of ignorance and supposition. This way, [doping] was smashed right into our face.|source=\u2013Tour director [[Jean-Marie Leblanc]] speaking about the fallout of the doping cases during the 1998 Tour{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=264}}|width=25%|align=right}}\nIn the direct aftermath of the Tour, there was a high number of raids and searches among cycling teams as well as riders questioned by police.{{efn|The [[Cantina Tollo]] team vehicles were searched upon entering Spain for the [[1998 Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n|Cl\u00e1sica de San Sebasti\u00e1n]], while {{ct|FDJ|1998}} had their cars searched when entering Germany to compete at the [[Regio-Tour]]. Meanwhile, [[Peter van Petegem]], a member of TVM, was called in to testify towards the suspicious exit of his former team {{ct|PDM|1991}} during the [[1991 Tour de France]], when Eric Ryckaert was working there as a team doctor.<ref name=cn_11august/>}} Two meetings to discuss the issue of doping were held shortly after the Tour. The first, between the UCI, race organisers and teams four days after the Tour ended in Paris, and a second on 11 August between the UCI and representatives of riders. Both meetings yielded little results.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pp=272\u2013273}} The riders voiced concern over the length of races and demanded changes to be made, while the question of a general amnesty for riders who took banned substances was also briefly discussed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Second Edition News for August 12, 1998: Drugs Update |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/aug98/aug12a.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=12 August 1998}}</ref> In a press communiqu\u00e9 released on 13 August, the UCI claimed that \"it is difficult to do more than is already being done\" in response to doping and that the blood tests enforced in 1997 enabled the UCI \"to control the EPO problem\", a claim that Alasdair Fotheringham later described as bordering \"on the delusional\".{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pp=273\u2013275}}\n\nFestina returned to racing shortly after the Tour de France, with the crowd showing positive responses to the team at the [[Vuelta a Burgos]]. The squad then competed in the last Grand Tour of the year, the [[1998 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Festina to turn the page |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1998/sep98/sep4.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=31 August 2019 |date=4 September 1998}}</ref> where Alex Z\u00fclle failed to defend his title, but won a stage and finished eighth overall.<ref>{{cite web |title=A\u00f1o 1998 |url=http://historia.lavuelta.com/es/anio.asp?a=1998 |website=LaVuelta.es |publisher=Unipublic |accessdate=31 August 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the fallout from the 1998 edition, the [[1999 Tour de France]] was dubbed by the organisers as the \"Tour of Renewal\", with the ASO publicly stating that they would welcome a lower average speed by around {{convert|3|kph|mph|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"cn_renewal\">{{cite web |last1=Qu\u00e9net |first1=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois |title=1999 Tour de France: The farce of renewal |url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/features/1999-tour-de-france-the-farce-of-renewal/ |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=2 September 2019 |date=27 June 2019}}</ref> This did not come to pass however, as the average speed rose again<ref name=\"cn_renewal\"/> and race winner [[Lance Armstrong]] was stripped of his title in 2012 following a lengthy investigation into doping practises.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Macur |first1=Juliet |title=Lance Armstrong Is Stripped of His 7 Tour de France Titles |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/23/sports/cycling/armstrong-stripped-of-his-7-tour-de-france-titles.html |accessdate=2 September 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=22 October 2012}}</ref> ASO barred the TVM team from competing in the 1999 race. Richard Virenque and Manolo Saiz were originally banned from the race, before the UCI required the race organisers to allow both to participate, considering that the ASO had failed to comply with a thirty-day registration period.<ref name=\"cn_renewal\"/> The Festina team was allowed to start the next Tour, following the organisers' assessment that, unlike at TVM, the doping culture in the team had changed.<ref>{{cite web |title=News for June 17, 1999 |url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/results/1999/jun99/jun17.shtml |website=[[Cyclingnews.com]] |accessdate=2 September 2019 |date=17 June 1999}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|quote=The Tour de France scandal highlighted the need for an independent international agency that would set harmonized standards for anti-doping work and coordinate the efforts of sports organizations and public authorities.|source=Official document of the [[World Anti-Doping Agency]] (WADA) on its own creation<ref>{{cite journal |title=1990s \u2013 A New Agency for a New Mission |journal=Play True |date=2009 |issue=2 |page=29 |url=https://www.wada-ama.org/sites/default/files/resources/files/PlayTrue_2009_2_Special_Tenth_Anniversary_EN.pdf |accessdate=6 September 2019}}</ref>|width=25%|align=right}}\nFotheringham noted nearly twenty years after the 1998 Tour that ever since, extraordinary performances in cycling have been viewed under a cover of suspicion of doping. Up until the revelations of the [[Lance Armstrong doping case]], the 1998 Tour de France stood as the biggest doping scandal in sport.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|pp=269\u2013270}} One of the most significant effects of the Festina affair was the creation of the [[World Anti-Doping Agency]] (WADA) in December 1999.{{sfn|Fotheringham|2017|p=271}}\n\n==In the media==\nIn 2018, a film centring around the 1998 Tour, titled ''The Domestique'' and to be directed by Kieron J. Walsh and written by Ciar\u00e1n Cassidy, was announced. Production was taken over by Blinder Films, with the movie receiving \u20ac800,000 funding through [[Screen Ireland]], the Irish state development agency.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shortall |first1=Eithne |title=Tour de Dopage film The Domestique passes test for Screen Ireland funding |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tour-de-dopage-film-the-domestique-passes-test-for-screen-ireland-funding-5t9wdq0dd |work=[[The Times]] |accessdate=12 June 2019 |date=22 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731145447/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tour-de-dopage-film-the-domestique-passes-test-for-screen-ireland-funding-5t9wdq0dd |archive-date=31 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film has since been renamed into ''The Racer'' and secured funding from Screen Flanders, the Film Fund Luxembourg, [[Eurimages]], the BAI Sound & Vision Fund, and [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RTE]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clarke |first1=Stewart |title=First Look at 1998 Tour de France Film \u2018The Racer\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/tour-de-france-film-the-racer-louis-talpe-iain-glen-1203282740/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=4 November 2019 |date=29 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports|France}}\n* [[1998 in sports]]\n* [[List of doping cases in cycling]]\n* [[Operaci\u00f3n Puerto doping case]]&nbsp;\u2013 a Spanish Police operation against mainly doping in professional cycling that began in 2006\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|publication-place=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Bacon|first=Ellis|title=Mapping Le Tour: Updated History and Route Map of Every Tour de France Race|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=628rngEACAAJ|year=2014|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|location=Glasgow, UK|isbn=978-0-00-754399-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Beth|last1=Edwards|first2=Lori|last2=Hobkirk|first3=Bryan|last3=Jew|first4=Tim|last4=Johnson|first5=Kip|last5=Mikler|first6=Rivvy|last6=Neshama|first7=Charles|last7=Pelkey|first8=John|last8=Rezell|first9=John|last9=Wilcockson|first10=Steve|last10=Wood|first11=Lennard|last11=Zinn|authorlink9=John Wilcockson|others=Featuring the Tour diaries of [[Frankie Andreu]]|title=Conquests and Crisis: The 1998 Tour de France|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X3FzOwAACAAJ|year=1998|publisher=VeloPress|location=Boulder, CO|isbn=978-1-884737-65-7|ref={{harvid|Edwards et al.|1998}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Fife|first=Graeme|author-link=Graeme Fife|title=Tour de France: The History, the Legend, the Riders|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ZeQ20Z4kcgC|year=2000|publisher=[[Mainstream Publishing]]|location=Edinburgh|isbn=978-1-84018-284-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Fotheringham|first=Alasdair|author-link=Alasdair Fotheringham|title=The End of the Road: The Festina Affair and the Tour that Almost Wrecked Cycling|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vGXGCwAAQBAJ|year=2017|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing]]|location=London|isbn=978-1-4729-1304-3|ref=harv}}\n*{{Citation|last=Friebe|first=Daniel|contribution=Il Pirata|editor-last1=Bacon|editor-first1=Ellis|editor-last2=Birnie|e